We introduce the notion of flow neighborhood $N_v(i)$ of data point $x_i$, where $k \in N_v(i)$ if $x_k$ is close to $x_i$ based on euclidean disatnce and the flow $\vec{v_i}$ at $x_i$ points towards the location of $x_k$. We have qualified these 2 qualities using our Flashlight Kernel. So the flow neighborhood $N_v(i)$ can be simply calculated as the n_neighbors data points (other than $x_i$ itself) with the highest (asymetric) affinity to $x_i$.

The function flow_neighbors returns a tensor of directed edge index where $(i,k)$ is an edge if $k \in N_v(i)$, i.e. $x_k$ is in the flow neighborhood of $x_i$, or $x_k$ is one of the n_neighbors data points with the highest affinity to $x_i$.

We test directed_neighbors on a simple circle. We would expect the flow neighborhood of any point to be the next n_neighbors points in the spiral.

{% raw %}
{% endraw %}

We visualize the flow neighborhoods as an adjacency matrix. As the data is neatly organized by the raidus around the spiral, we would aspect the flow neighbors to all be on the upper triangle along the main diagonal.

Notice that for the last few data points, since the flows there is pointing outwards to no other data points, the flow neighbors end up being preceding points in the spiral simply because the points are euclideanly close to one another.

{% raw %} 
from FRED.data_processing import affinity_matrix_from_pointset_to_pointset
from FRED.datasets import visualize_edge_index
import torch

X = torch.tensor(X).float()
flows = torch.tensor(flows).float()

P_graph = affinity_matrix_from_pointset_to_pointset(X, X, flows, sigma=1, flow_strength=0.5)

neighbors = flow_neighbors(X.shape[0], P_graph, n_neighbors=10)
visualize_edge_index(neighbors)
